.TH "IFCFG\-IPVTAP" "5" "November 2024" "Wicked User Manual" ""
.SH NAME
ifcfg\-ipvtap \- IPVTAP interface configuration
.SH SYNOPSIS
\f[CR]/etc/sysconfig/network/ifcfg\-*\f[R]
.SH IPVTAP interface
To set up an IPVTAP interface, you need a configuration file with the
\f[CR]IPVTAP=yes\f[R] variable set.
.PP
An IPVTAP interface is conceptually similar to MACVTAP with the same
difference between MACVLAN and IPVLAN.
The IPVTAP interface operate on Layer 3 and share the same configuration
options with IPVLAN.
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
\f[CR]IPVTAP <yes|no>\f[R]
This option must be set to \f[B]yes\f[R] to identify this configuration
type as IPVTAP.
.TP
\f[CR]IPVTAP_DEVICE\f[R]
Mandatory option to specify the lower (parent) interface for this IPVTAP
interface.
.TP
\f[CR]IPVTAP_MODE <l2|l3|l3s>\f[R]
Specifies the mode for the IPVTAP interface.
For a given lower device, you can select one of these modes and all
linked devices will operate in the same mode.
.RS
.PP
Default: \f[B]l3\f[R]
.RE
.TP
\f[CR]IPVTAP_FLAGS <bridge|private|vepa>\f[R]
Specifies the mode flags.
Only one flag at a time is allowed.
Similar to \f[CR]IPVTAP_MODE\f[R], a given flag will be applied to all
linked devices of one lower interface.
.RS
.PP
Default: \f[B]bridge\f[R]
.RE
.SH EXAMPLES
Example \f[CR]ifcfg\-<name>\f[R] config file for an IPVTAP interface
.IP
.EX
STARTMODE=auto
BOOTPROTO=static
IPADDR=10.0.0.100/24

IPVTAP=yes
IPVTAP_DEVICE=eth0
IPVTAP_MODE=l3s
IPVTAP_FLAGS=bridge
.EE
